This document maps the pipeline from source dictionary to four compiled artifacts (`out/plain-ts.json`, `out/smart-ts.json`, `out/vim-snippets.json`, `out/snippets.json`). It's the architecture reference — the mandatory read before touching expand/, render/, or snippet/.

Data flows strictly forward through parsing (text → AST), Pass A (count expansion), Pass B (type append), line-flag variant generation, then three parallel renders. Each pass has its own error type; nothing is swallowed. Parse, expand, and the two renders are coupled: Pass A's scope of `d` must match its use in both `%d` and `%(EXPR)` expressions; Pass B's "family root" detection in `fix_family_terminals` (expand/family.rs) is load-bearing for the terminal flag that `render/mod.rs`'s `build_dict` relies on to forbid type-append intermediates in plain/smart outputs (they're allowed only in snippets, as non-tabstop partials with a `{^}…{^}` sentinel). The smart renderer must drop exactly the trailing run of auto-supplied closers that the `SMART` profile's `auto_close` behavior would emit; collision detection happens after all three renders finish.

The infinite path (dict.infinite.steno → C++ header) is a strict fork: it runs parse and Pass A only, skips Pass B enumeration entirely, and instead emits two finite tables (type and construct) consumed at lookup time by a C++ walker that reconstructs definitions on-device. The walker's behavior is pinned to Pass B via differential test (scripts/cpp_check.sh under cargo test); a silent divergence corrupts output, so agreement is enforced by test, not asserted. The `@fuse` / `%T` multi-slot semantics require `check_fuse_ambiguity` to validate that no two `(shape, type head)` pairs merge to the same stroke.

Module dependencies are strictly acyclic (parse ← expand ← render/snippet/blocks; json_out is a leaf). Error handling is typed and complete: five error types across five owners (parse, stroke mechanics, Pass A/B, render, snippet), each carrying message and (for parse) source location.